Maven:
Maven is a build + dependency management tool for Java projects
Maven is a build automation and dependency management tool that uses a pom.xml file to manage project configuration, dependencies
and lifecycle phases like compile, test, and package.

POM = Project Object Model 
It is a Heart of Maven
It contains:Project info , Dependencies , Plugins , Build configuration

Maven Life Cycle:
clean → validate → compile → test → package → verify → install → deploy

Maven integration with Jenkins allows automated build, test, and packaging of applications using Maven lifecycle phases within a CI/CD pipeline.

There are 2 different things:
| Type                     | Meaning                             |
| ------------------------ | ----------------------------------- |
| ✅ Maven (tool)           | Installed on server (`mvn` command) |
| ✅ Maven plugin (Jenkins) | Plugin inside Jenkins UI            |

In Jenkins pipelines, Maven is used as a configured tool and executed via shell commands, so the
Maven Integration Plugin is not required unless using freestyle jobs.

Step 1: Prepare Ubuntu VM-----------Install Java + Maven:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install openjdk-17-jdk -y
sudo apt install maven -y

java -version
mvn -version

Step 2: Install & Setup Jenkins
sudo apt install jenkins -y
sudo systemctl start jenkins
sudo systemctl enable jenkins

step 3: Access via browser 
http://<your-ip>:8080

Step 4: Configure Tools in Jenkins
Go to: Manage Jenkins → Global Tool Configuration

✅ Add JDK

| Field | Value                                |
| ----- | ------------------------------------ |
| Name  | `jdk17`                              |
| Path  | `/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk-amd64` |

✅ Add Maven

| Field                 | Value          |
| --------------------- | -------------- |
| Name                  | `maven_3.9.14` |
| Install automatically | ✔              |

Step 5: Create Jenkins Pipeline Job
Go to Jenkins ----- Click New Item-----Select Pipeline------Give name: maven-pipeline

Step 9: Automate with Git Webhook
In GitHub: Settings → Webhooks
Add: http://<jenkins-ip>:8080/github-webhook/
✔ Now build triggers automatically



